\par }{\b\fs24 <I> <h> Ozone level dips lowest </h>
\par }{\fs24 <#/>THE amount of protective ozone in the atmosphere over Antarctica dipped to its lowest level ever recorded, the U.S. Space Agency (NASA)said last week. 
\par <#/>Scientists using NASA's total ozone mapping spectrometre (toms) observed ozone levels as low as 110 dobson unites - a measure of the number of ozone molecules per square centimetre. 
\par <#/>"The minimum ozone on October 6, 1991, is the lowest we have ever seen with the toms instrument in its 13-year record of data," said Arlin Krueger, a scientist with the National Aeronautics and Space Administration. 
\par <#/>As of October 1, the lowest level of ozone seen by toms was 127 dobson Units, NASA said. 
\par <#/>Ozone, a molecule made up of three oxygen atoms, acts as a shield against solar ultraviolet radiation which can raise the risk of cancer in humans and threaten food crops. 
\par <#/>While research has blamed man-made chlorine compounds and other chemicals for ozone depletion, the extreme dip in this year's Antarctic ozone cannot be attributed solely to chemical processes, NASA said. 
\par <#/>The scientists said that weather can cause fluctuations inside a chemically produced ozone hole, which typically is observed from late August through mid-November. </I>
