\par <I> <h> Serengeti Lions hit by CDV </h>
\par }{\fs24 <#/>
A mysterious disease has struck the lions in the Serengeti National Park in Arusha Region, killing about 80 of them. <#/>Our Correspondent, <name/>, was recently in Arusha where he talked to research scientists on the epidemic which might threaten the lar
gest lion prides in the world. 
\par <#/>A mysterious disease, which scientists have identified as "}{\i\fs24 canine distemper virus}{\fs24 " (CDV), has struck the lion population in the Serengeti National Park in Arusha Region. 
\par <#/>At least 21 of them have been confirmed to have died from the virus given the laboratory analysis carried out locally and abroad. 
\par <#/>About 64 other lions, which have been observed regularly in the past years, have disappeared and are presumed to have been killed by the viral disease which could be threatening the world's largest remaining population of the king of the jungle. 

\par <#/>American scientists, Dr. Craig Packer and Dr. Melody Roelke who have been collecting blood and tissue samples from the animals, said in Arusha recently that the disease may have killed more lions than is known. 
\par <#/>"Of the 250 or so study animals we have been following, perhaps a third have been wiped out by what we've found out to be distemper and many more are sick," they said. 
\par <#/>CDV was originally a domestic dog disease, they said. <#/>But this was the first time that the vi\-rus is confirmed to have attacked cat-family animals like the lions. 
\par <#/>The virus causes convulsions, muscle twitching, depression, loss of appetite, later resulting in severe neurological symptoms and death. 
\par <#/>The dying lions observed were unable to stand because of severe convulsions and one animal repeatedly turned in tight circles, Dr. Roelke said. 
\par <#/>"Others showed signs of persistent  twitches and facial contortions while some jerked and flailed their paws when they  relax", she added. 
\par }\pard\plain \s16\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang1031 {<#/>}{\lang2057 Prides of lions in the Serengeti have been under intensive study for almost 30 years now. <#/> But it was at the beginning of this year that bodies of dea
d lions were seen by researchers. <#/>Initially, the cause of the death was elusive. 
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057 {<#/>}{\fs24 According to Dr. Roelke, between February and May, this year, eight lions in the southern part of the park were observed with severe neurological disorders followed b
y death or disappearance. 
\par <#/>A close observation by the monitoring team has found that 84 of the 250 lions regularly monitored were missing and could have been wiped out by the }{\i\fs24 distemper}{\fs24 . 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>Intensive investigation was initiated by the Tanzania Nationa
l Parks (TANAPA) since April, this year, after first reports of the outbreak appeared in the foreign press. <#/>TANAPA manages Serengeti and several other game parks in the country. 
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057 {<#/>}{\fs24 Veterinarians led by Dr: Roelke attached to the Serengeti Wildlife Re
search Centre collected blood and tissue samples from 60 lions and sent them for study to several universities in Tanzania, the United States and Switzerland. 
\par <#/>According to her, preliminary studies found }{\i\fs24 canine distemper}{\fs24  }{\i\fs24 virus}{\fs24  was the primary disease agent, accounting for 87 per cent of the victims examined. 
\par <#/>"Fifty-two of the 60 lions (or 87 per cent) had high levels of CDV anti-bodies in their blood and many of the examined  tissues showed microscopic evi\-dence of CDV viral particles", she added
\par }\pard\plain \s17\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {T
